  "diagnostic_reasoning": "High oil consumption (adding a quart every 4-5 hours) points to either external oil leaks or internal engine oil burning. The Service Manual lists specific external leak points such as a 'Damaged crankshaft seal' or 'Damaged push rod housing oil seal' as probable causes for oil leaks (Source 43). It also generally advises checking for 'oil and fuel leaks' in the engine compartment (Source 32). Internal oil burning is typically due to worn piston rings, cylinder walls, or valve guides, which would be indicated by blue exhaust smoke. While the manual doesn't have a direct troubleshooting entry for 'high oil consumption,' it does mention 'high oil consumption may be experienced' if incorrect oil is used during break-in (Source 1, 28), implying internal engine condition is a factor. Furthermore, 'Defective engine' requiring 'compression check' is listed as a probable cause for 'ENGINE RUNS ROUGHLY OR WILL NOT ACCELERATE PROPERLY' (Source 9, 49, 51), which could be related to internal wear causing oil consumption. Dirty or diluted oil can also contribute to wear (Source 23, 29). I need to determine if the oil is leaking externally or being consumed internally.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "A quart of oil every 4-5 hours is excessive consumption. We need to determine if this oil is leaking externally or being burned internally. Start by performing a thorough visual inspection for leaks and observing the exhaust.",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "I see visible oil streaks or puddles on the engine, cowling, or hangar floor.",
    "I see blue smoke from the exhaust, especially on engine start-up or during power changes.",
    "I see no visible leaks or blue smoke, but the oil on the dipstick appears dirty or diluted quickly after an oil change.",
    "The engine is new or recently overhauled (within 50 hours of operation)."
  ],
  "requires_input": true
}

